13: One way to identify archive-specic resources is to look at the HTTP Response header \Link" that contains \http://mementoweb.org/terms/donotnegotiate".

As shown in Figure 13, archives should respond with the HTTP \Link" header containing \ http://mementoweb.org/terms/donotnegot iate " and \ rel="type" " to requests for resources which are not mementos and are excluded from content negotiation based on the time dimension.

For example https://web.archive.org/web/20100923005105id_/http://www.cnn.co m:80/ will return the raw content of the memento https://web.archive.org/web/20100923005105/http://www.cnn.com:8 0/ Even though using id is benecial for raw content retrieval, it might cause issues, such as links to resources constructing a memento not being rewritten to point to an archive, which prevents the memento from being replayed appropri- ately as Figure 14 shows.

Malicious code is injected in the live web resource http://cdn.projecthaile.com/js/trb-1.js By requesting this resource as a part of constructing the memento http://web.archive.org/web/20110901233330/reuters.com it causes a user's view to be completely controlled by the malicious code.
